\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 What sets T_rad in reality:
\f0\b0  The radiator surface temperature is not a free design parameter \'97 it's determined by the thermal resistance chain from the chip junction down to the radiator face. Roughly: T_rad = T_chip \uc0\u8722  (Q \'d7 R_thermal), where R_thermal includes the cold plate, the working fluid loop, the heat pipe condenser, and the panel-to-coating interface. Modern GPU junction temperatures are capped around 85\'9695\'b0C (358\'96368 K). If you can run the radiator at 350 K (still well below chip limits), your required area drops by more than half versus the 300 K assumption. This is probably the most important refinement to add to the model.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 10. Radiator faces away from the Sun (P_solar \uc0\u8776  0)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Assumption:
\f0\b0  The radiator is oriented toward deep space, so the direct solar term is zeroed out. This is the optimal attitude for cooling.\

\f1\b What this requires:
\f0\b0  Active attitude control to maintain this orientation throughout the orbit. The PV array simultaneously needs to face the Sun, and the radiator needs to face away \'97 these are geometrically compatible for a well-designed structure (PV on the sun-facing side, radiator on the deep-space-facing side), but any attitude control failure immediately loads the radiator with up to 1367 \'d7 \uc0\u945 _solar \'d7 A_rad of solar heat. Even at \u945  = 0.05, that's ~68 W/m\'b2 \'97 more than the Earth IR term.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 11. Earth IR: H_earth = 237 W/m\'b2\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Assumption:
\f0\b0  Constant planetary infrared emission, taken directly from Fan et al. This is the global annual average.\

\f1\b What varies in reality:
\f0\b0  Earth's IR emission varies with latitude, season, and cloud cover. Polar orbits see systematically lower values (~220 W/m\'b2); tropical orbits see higher (~260 W/m\'b2). At 400 km, the spacecraft completes one orbit every ~92 minutes so it averages over a range of conditions. The 237 W/m\'b2 is a defensible central estimate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 12. Earth albedo R_earth = 0.30\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Assumption:
\f0\b0  Global average Bond albedo, also from Fan et al. The actual albedo varies from ~0.06 over oceans to ~0.90 over fresh snow, and the albedo term in our model is small anyway (6.8 vs. 70.5 W/m\'b2 for Earth IR), so this assumption has minimal impact on the result.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

